🙌🏻Grooming. It's a topic that all dog owners should be aware of. Every breed of dog will have their own individual grooming needs and you should always consult your professional groomer and your veterinarian for any specific questions about your dogs physical health. Here I am with Fulton demonstrating proper canine oral health. You should brush the inside and outside of all of the teeth and up near the gums. (And no, he's not sedated. He's trained to stay still during teeth brushing and to hold his tongue still). Start them young! We brush our dogs teeth roughly twice a week, they also eat raw diet food instead of kibble. This promotes healthy gums and clean teeth without plaque or cavities. Dental health is important; unhealthy teeth can lead to heart disease and untimely expiration of your best friend. You brush your teeth every day, so you should also keep up with your dogs oral health. Ears are a huge problem during summer! During fun activities such as swimming, we can forget to clean our dogs ears. Forgetting this simple step can lead to infections and then weeks without being able to swim! Never put any liquid into your dogs ears intentionally without consulting your vet, and never stick anything like cotton or swabs into their ears. You can ask your veterinarian about the best way to clean your dogs ears after swimming! Brushing is another neglected topic especially with short haired pups. Even though they have short hair, you should still brush and condition their fur and skin. We brush our dogs 2-3x per day. Brushing decreases ingrown hairs and staph infections that can occur under collars, harnesses, and other gear. Keep your dogs coat and fur clear of dirt, dander, fleas and ticks by using monthly preventatives and weekly baths. We use WAHL oatmeal shampoo and Heartguard and Nexguard for flea and tick. Summer is notorious for bug bites, and deaths by Tick bites and flea anemia. Protect your best friend and keep them clean! They will love you for it! 😍 #dogs #grooming #consultyourdoggroomer #veterinarian #healthtips #healthydog #healthy #dentalhygiene #fur #teethwhitening #careforyourdog #keepyourdoghealth

The photo on the left was May 17, 2014, three years ago TODAY. .
I remember it well because Anderson turned 2 months old and I received clearance for exercise from my midwife. Well, the first time I attempted a workout I sat on my floor and cried. I had lost my physical strength during pregnancy, but the real problem was that I had also lost all my confidence. I was physically and mentally weak and though I was so in love with my little family, in that moment I felt entirely discouraged and helpless. I was a new mom, who was REALLY struggling. .
Dedicating myself to live a healthier life was unbelievably challenging at first, but fitness saved me-- it sounds dramatic but it's true. I gained physical strength but I also gained a self love and self confidence I had longed for my whole life.
.
That is why my first SELF program I created is for post-pregnancy training -- knowing that I am now able to provide help for someone who might currently be feeling like I used to, is honestly the most incredible and humbling feeling in the world.
.
I will never forget how I felt that day three years ago. I will never stop striving to be my best self, INSIDE and out. I will never stop working hard to do all I can to help YOU on your journey to do the same. I will never stop being amazed at the support you show me as I try to do so, and the support you give each other along the way. 💧💪🏼 www.kelseywells.com/app .
